Since an ASCII character (like 'A' or '\n') is exactly 8 bits (1 byte) long,
outb is the exact instruction we need to blast characters to the serial port.

writing Assembly every time we want to print a character is going to get miserable fast. To fix this,
kernel developers wrap these Assembly instructions inside standard C functions using a GCC feature called inline assembly (__asm__ volatile).

This helps us to create a C function that looks like this:
void outb(uint16_t port, uint8_t data); so that now we can use this directly without writing codes again and again for each letter.

If we want to print a long message like "Hello", we would have to write raw assembly code for the letter 'H', then more assembly for 'e', then 'l',
and so on. Doing this every single time would quickly become exhausting and difficult to read.

To make life easier(still tough:[ ), we can wrap that ugly assembly code inside a neat, clean C function.
we use a special GCC feature called inline assembly (__asm__ volatile). Think of this like building a button labeled outb(port, data) in C.

the GCC compiler automatically pulls the lever, replaces that line of C code, and inserts the exact,
raw out machine instruction directly into our operating system's final binary file.
We get the speed and power of assembly, but with the cleanliness of C code. (WOW... even i was loving this in the beginning, but only the beginning.)

this is the blueprint we have: __asm__ volatile ("assembly code" : output_operands : input_operands : clobbered_registers);
now, AT&T syntax has a format as: instruction source, destination, also requires a percent sign (%) before register names.
But since we want GCC to automatically choose the registers for our C variables, we use a number placeholder instead, like %0 and %1.
%0 represents our data and %1 represents our port. this will look like "outb %0,%1". (i was way too proud writing this line XD)

output_operands: this is for when the asm code gives somthing back to us. Since sending a byte to a serial port is a one-way trip, we are pushing data out,
and we ain't excepting anything back.. so we can leave this as : aka empty.

input_operands: now here we hve to think as take my C variables port and data, and put them into the exact CPU registers that the outb instruction demands.
GCC uses specific single-letter codes (constraints) to match variables to CPU registers. (i remember learning this regs as AX,BX,CX,DX in microprocessors).
-> "a" constraint, This forces GCC to use the AL / AX / EAX register. x86 CPU's out instruction strictly requires the data we want to send to be inside this specific register.
(i remeber doing this sort of some expt in lab using the 8086 emulator, that day i cussed at the pc i mean thats everyday).
-> "d" constraint: This forces GCC to use the DX register. x86 CPU strictly requires the destination port number to be held in this register. (ya sure bro)

clobbered_registers: assembly code manually overrides or messes up any other CPU registers during its execution, we must list them here so the compiler knows to save their contents beforehand.
for outb, instruction safely sends data out of the CPU to the motherboard without changing any internal registers. so we dont need to bother abt this.

//static means this function is local to the file, Because inline copy-pastes the code everywhere, you don't want the linker to get confused and complain about "duplicate function definitions" across different files.
static keeps it neatly contained.
// 'inline' tells the compiler to copy-paste this raw assembly code directly where it is called. This removes the time wasted jumping back and forth to a function, making the kernel faster.

//__asm__ This tells GCC to stop reading C instructions for a moment and prepare to drop raw CPU assembly language directly into the final compiled binary.
//volatile (aka do not touch) Compilers are incredibly smart and aggressive. If GCC looks at your C code and thinks a line isn't doing anything useful for the C environment, it might delete it or move it around to optimize speed.
you are strictly commanding GCC: "Do not optimize this, do not move it, and do not delete it. Execute this exact instruction, at this exact moment, no matter what."
static inline void outb(uint16_t port, uint8_t data) { // imagine as button outb(0x3F8, 'A') this will print A
    __asm__ volatile ("outb %0, %1" : : "a"(data), "d"(port)); // crazy ryt, ik im overreacting but yeah, i love this
}

